            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the Maine income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates your
                <strong>Maine state income tax</strong> using the latest
                published brackets, standard deduction, and personal exemption
                amounts for the selected tax year. It is designed as a planning
                aid and does not replace official forms or professional advice.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Start with your Maine adjusted gross income</h3>
              <p>We first combine your entries for:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Wages &amp; salary</strong> (W‑2 income)</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Other taxable income</strong> (interest, side jobs,
                  etc.)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Minus <strong>pre‑tax deductions</strong> such as 401(k),
                  traditional IRA, or HSA contributions
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This gives an estimate of your
                <strong>Maine adjusted gross income (AGI)</strong>.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>AGI ≈</strong> Wages + Other income − Pre‑tax
                  deductions
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Subtract deductions</h3>
              <p>
                Maine allows either a <strong>standard deduction</strong> or
                <strong>itemized deductions</strong>
                (generally based on your federal itemized deductions with Maine
                adjustments).
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  If you choose <strong>Standard deduction</strong>, the
                  calculator applies the Maine amount for your filing status.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you choose <strong>Itemized deductions</strong>, we
                  subtract the amount you enter.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Maine taxable income ≈</strong> AGI − Deductions −
                  Personal exemptions
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Apply Maine tax brackets</h3>
              <p>
                Maine uses a <strong>progressive tax system</strong>: different
                portions of your taxable income are taxed at different rates.
                For each filing status and year, the calculator:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Splits your taxable income across the Maine brackets.</li>
                <li>Applies the correct rate to each slice.</li>
                <li>
                  Sums the results to get your
                  <strong>total Maine income tax</strong>.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <p>
                The table in the results panel shows exactly how much of your
                income falls into each bracket and the tax owed in that bracket.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Effective vs. marginal Maine tax rate</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective tax rate</strong> = Maine tax ÷ total
                  income. This is your overall average rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Marginal tax rate</strong> is the rate on your
                  <em>last dollar</em> of Maine taxable income (the highest
                  bracket you reach).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Effective rate</strong> = Maine tax / Total income
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Marginal rate</strong> = Top bracket rate that applies
                  to you
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The calculator focuses on
                  <strong>Maine state income tax only</strong> (no federal,
                  Social Security, or Medicare).
                </li>
                <li>
                  It assumes all income you enter is
                  <strong>Maine‑taxable</strong> and from Maine residents.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Credits (such as child tax credits or property tax fairness
                  credits) are modeled in a simplified way as a per‑dependent
                  estimate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Special situations (nonresidents, part‑year residents,
                  business income apportionment, complex credits) are not fully
                  modeled.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For complex situations, consult a tax professional or the
                official Maine Revenue Services resources.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about Maine income tax</h2>

              <h3>Does Maine have a flat income tax rate?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Maine uses a <strong>progressive</strong> income tax system
                with multiple brackets. Higher levels of taxable income are
                taxed at higher marginal rates.
              </p>

              <h3>Are Social Security benefits taxed in Maine?</h3>
              <p>
                Maine generally <strong>follows federal rules</strong> for
                Social Security taxation, but also allows certain pension and
                Social Security deductions. This calculator does not separately
                model those; if you receive Social Security, you can approximate
                by entering only the portion that is federally taxable.
              </p>

              <h3>How do Maine standard and itemized deductions work?</h3>
              <p>
                Maine offers a <strong>standard deduction</strong> that varies
                by filing status, or you can claim
                <strong>itemized deductions</strong> if they exceed the standard
                amount and you qualify. Itemized deductions are often based on
                your federal Schedule A, with Maine‑specific adjustments.
              </p>

              <h3>Do local cities in Maine charge additional income tax?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Maine does <strong>not</strong> have local or city income
                taxes on top of the state income tax. However, local property
                taxes and other fees may apply.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this calculator an official Maine tax tool?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This is an <strong>independent estimator</strong> for
                educational and planning purposes. For official forms,
                instructions, and the latest law changes, visit
                <a
                  href="https://www.maine.gov/revenue/"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener"
                  >Maine Revenue Services</a
                >.
              </p>
